# My self-hosted stack

This self-hosted stack is generated from the template at: https://github.com/mschoettle/self-hosted

## Features of this stack

- reverse proxy via [`traefik`](https://doc.traefik.io/traefik/)
    - [Let's Encrypt ACME challenge](https://doc.traefik.io/traefik/reference/install-configuration/tls/certificate-resolvers/acme/#the-different-acme-challenges): {{ letsencrypt_challenge | upper }}
{%- if use_pihole %}
- [Pi-hole](https://pi-hole.net/): Network-wide ad blocking
{%- endif %}
{%- if needs_db %}
- [PostgreSQL](https://www.postgresql.org/) database
{%- endif %}
{%- if use_nextcloud %}
- [Nextcloud](https://nextcloud.com/): Content collaboration platform, e.g., used for file hosting
    - [Valkey](https://valkey.io/) (a Redis fork) is used for [memory caching](https://docs.nextcloud.com/server/stable/admin_manual/configuration_server/caching_configuration.html#recommendations-based-on-type-of-deployment)
{%- endif %}
{%- if use_forgejo %}
- [Forgejo](https://forgejo.org/): Git hosting with collaborative features (like GitHub)
{%- endif %}
{%- if use_umami %}
- [Umami](https://umami.is/): Privacy-focused web analytics
{%- endif %}

## Getting Started

1. Initialize a Git repository and version changes to your stack.

    ```shell
    git init
    ```

1. Define missing env variables in `.env`
  - `TIMEZONE`: the timezone your stack is running in as a [TZ identifier](ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tz_database_time_zones)
  - `TRAEFIK_ACME_PATH`: the directory where the certificates on your host
  - `TRAEFIK_LOGS_PATH`: the directory where the access logs on your host
{%- if letsencrypt_challenge == 'dns' %}
1. Add the name of the DNS provider to `traefik.yaml` in `certificatesResolvers.letsencrypt.acme.dnsChallenge.provider`
1. Add the [environment variables for your DNS provider](https://go-acme.github.io/lego/dns/) to `.envs/letsencrypt.env`
    - We recommend using [secrets](https://docs.docker.com/reference/compose-file/secrets/) for API keys and passwords
    - We recommend using an [override file](https://docs.docker.com/compose/how-tos/multiple-compose-files/merge/) to merge these settings with the generated compose file and avoid conflicts when updating to a new template version
{%- endif %}
1. Create directories for all the volume paths you defined

{%- if needs_db %}
### Database

Define the missing environment variables in `.env`:

- `POSTGRESDB_VOLUME_PATH`: the directory where the PostgreSQL data on your host

Define the root password in `.secrets/db_root_password`.

{%- endif %}

{%- if use_nextcloud %}
### Nextcloud

Define the missing environment variables in `.env`:

- `NEXTCLOUD_VOLUME_PATH`: the directory where the Nextcloud data on your host
- `NEXTCLOUD_DOMAIN`: the domain/hostname the Nextcloud instance will be reachable at
- `NEXTCLOUD_TRUSTED_PROXIES`: the IP address of your reverse proxy (traefik) to be a [trusted proxy](https://docs.nextcloud.com/server/stable/admin_manual/configuration_server/reverse_proxy_configuration.html)
  ```shell
  {% raw %}docker inspect traefik --format "{{range .NetworkSettings.Networks}}{{.IPAddress}}{{end}}"{% endraw %}
  ```
- `VALKEY_VOLUME_PATH`: the directory where the Valkey data on your host

Create a dedicated database user and database for Nextcloud:

```shell
./scripts/psql_create.sh --user nextcloud --database nextcloud --password <password>
```

Bring the container up:

```shell
docker compose up -d nextcloud
```

You can now access the Nextcloud instance and initiate the setup process.

Once that is done, check the setup via the [`setupchecks` command](https://docs.nextcloud.com/server/stable/admin_manual/occ_command.html#setupchecks-commands-label):

```shell
docker compose exec --user www-data php occ setupchecks
```

You can also perform system checks when logging in to the UI as an administrator and navigating to _Administration Settings_ (`/settings/admin/overview`).

Address any findings, such as the maintenance window start.
The config file is located at `$NEXTCLOUD_VOLUME_PATH/config/config.php`.
See the [Nextcloud configuration documentation](https://docs.nextcloud.com/server/latest/admin_manual/configuration_server/index.html) for more information.
{%- endif %}

## Updating

To update your stack to a new version, run the following command:

```shell
copier update --trust
```

Or, via the [`uvx command`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/guides/tools/#running-tools) of [`uv`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/):

```shell
uvx --with copier-templates-extensions copier update --trust
```
